{"slug": "haunt", "root": "haunt", "category": "act", "gloss": "to be troubled by a spirit", "definition": "To *haunt* is for a spirit or the dead to trouble a place or person by lingering there — returning, unbidden, to a house, a road, or a grave. It differs from *possess*, which enters and inhabits a living body: a haunting clings to a location and disturbs from outside, where possession seizes a self from within. The ghost haunts because it will not leave.", "history": "Old French *hanter* meant simply 'to frequent, resort to' — to keep going somewhere — with no ghost in it; a hunter's *haunts* were just the places game gathered. The turn is late and English: because the returning dead were imagined as spirits who *kept frequenting* the places they had known, 'haunt' took on its spectral sense. Renaissance sources still show both — Keith Thomas records the belief in ghosts revisiting their haunts from purgatory, and Zambelli notes husbands' ghosts who came back to haunt their widows. Magic: The Gathering makes it a keyword for spirits that cling on.", "def_sources": [{"label": "Thomas, Religion and the Decline of Magic (ghosts revisiting their haunts)", "where": "Renaissance magic (PDF)", "url": "https://www.penguin.co.uk/books/13672/religion-and-the-decline-of-magic-by-keith-thomas/9780140137446", "url_kind": "publisher", "abstract": "A landmark history of why belief in witchcraft, astrology, and protective charms was so common in 16th- and 17th-century England, and how the rise of Protestant religion and early science gradually pushed those beliefs to the margins of everyday life."}, {"label": "Paola Zambelli, White Magic, Black Magic in the European Renaissance (ghosts returning to haunt)", "where": "Renaissance magic (PDF)", "url": "https://brill.com/display/title/11995?language=en", "url_kind": "publisher", "abstract": "Examines Renaissance thinkers' theories about magic, focusing especially on how learned 'high' magic practiced by scholars overlapped and interacted with everyday popular magic and witchcraft accusations among ordinary people."}, {"label": "Etymonline, s.v. haunt", "where": "Etymology reference"}], "commentary": null, "commentary_sources": [], "is_keyword": true, "etymology": {"lang": "French", "origin": "Old French hanter 'to frequent, resort to'", "first": "c. 1300; ghostly sense mid-1500s", "note": "To haunt first meant merely 'to hang around a place'. Ghosts haunt because they keep frequenting; the spooky sense is a late English gift.", "hook": "Ghosts don't haunt — they just won't leave."}, "essay": null, "sources": ["Etymonline (Douglas Harper)", "Wiktionary", "classical lexica (Lewis & Short, LSJ, Bosworth–Toller)", "Ted's historical-magic DBs (WitchcraftStudiesDB, AgrippaDOP, MedievalMagicDB)"], "stats": {"flavor_total": 41, "oracle_total": 42, "in_flavor_cards": 41, "in_oracle_cards": 18, "name_match_count": 38, "by_variant": {"haunt": 27, "haunting": 22, "haunted": 21, "haunts": 13}, "first_year": 1994, "colors": {"B": 45, "G": 11, "U": 16, "W": 18, "C": 10, "R": 7}, "by_year": {"1994": 1, "1996": 1, "1997": 2, "1999": 2, "2001": 3, "2002": 1, "2003": 1, "2004": 1, "2006": 8, "2009": 2, "2010": 2, "2011": 1, "2012": 3, "2013": 1, "2014": 2, "2015": 1, "2016": 2, "2017": 1, "2018": 5, "2019": 2, "2020": 2, "2021": 11, "2022": 11, "2023": 4, "2024": 8, "2025": 4, "2026": 5}}, "cards": [{"id": "cbd2d38b-6402-44b7-ba27-d854268e31d0", "name": "Haunting Wind", "set": "ATQ", "set_name": "Antiquities", "released": "1994-03-04", "type_line": "Enchantment", "rarity": "uncommon", "colors": ["B"], "img_small": "https://cards.scryfall.io/small/front/a/2/a2f6ef2f-a3a2-4e1f-b7eb-59abc8414114.jpg?1782722570", "img_normal": "https://cards.scryfall.io/normal/front/a/2/a2f6ef2f-a3a2-4e1f-b7eb-59abc8414114.jpg?1782722570", "scryfall_uri": "https://scryfall.com/card/atq/17/haunting-wind?utm_source=api", "local": "img/haunt/cbd2d38b-6402-44b7-ba27-d854268e31d0.jpg"}, {"id": "ced9130c-2865-49df-abdd-84069aa1b180", 